<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-section-PointsOnGraphs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Effect of transformations on points</title>

  <p> While the corresponding points on the graphs of vertical transformations
    may seem clear, the corresponding points on the graphs of the horizontal
    transformations can create some confusion. Let's see the logic argument behind
    the characterization we observed. </p>

  <p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-PointsHorizontalShift">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let the graph of <m>g</m> be a horizontal shift of <m>h</m> units of the graph of <m>f</m>. If the point <m>(x,y)</m> lies on the graph of <m>f</m>, then the point <m>(x+h,y)</m> lies on the graph of <m>g</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
  </p>

  <p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>y=f(x)</m> be a function with domain <m>D</m>. By definition
        <md>
          Graph(f)=\lbrace (x,y):x\in D\rbrace
        </md>
        Let <m>g</m> be a function with domain <m>E</m> defined by <m>g(z)=f(z-h)</m> (a horizontal shift of <m>f</m> by <m>h</m> units.)
        Then <m>z-h\in D</m>. Write <m>x=z-h</m> for some <m>x\in D</m>.
        Then
        <md>
          <mrow>Graph(g)= \amp \lbrace (z,g(z)):z\in E\rbrace</mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \lbrace (z,f(z-h)):z\in E\rbrace</mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \lbrace (x+h,f((x+h)-h)):x\in D\rbrace </mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \lbrace (x+h,f(x)):x\in D\rbrace</mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \lbrace (x+h,y):x\in D\rbrace</mrow>
        </md>
         
      </p>
    </proof>
  </p>

  <p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-PointsHorizontalDilation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let the graph of <m>g</m> be a horizontal dilation of the graph of <m>f</m>, i.e., <m>g(x)=f(Bx)</m>. If the point <m>(x,y)</m> lies on the graph of <m>f</m>, then the point <m>\left(\frac{x}{B},y\right)</m> lies on the graph of <m>g</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
  </p>

  <p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>y=f(x)</m> be a function with domain <m>D</m>. By definition
        <md>
          Graph(f)=\lbrace (x,y):x\in D\rbrace
        </md>
        Let <m>g</m> be a function with domain <m>E</m> defined by <m>g(z)=f(Bz)</m> (a horizontal dilation of <m>f</m>.)
        Then <m>Bz\in D</m>. Write <m>x=Bz</m> for some <m>x\in D</m>.
        Then
        <md>
          <mrow>Graph(g)= \amp \lbrace (z,g(z)):z\in E\rbrace</mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \lbrace (z,f(Bz)):z\in E\rbrace</mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \left\lbrace \left(\frac{x}{B},f\left(B\left(\frac{x}{B}\right)\right)\right):x\in D\right\rbrace </mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \left\lbrace \left(\frac{x}{B},f(x)\right):x\in D\right\rbrace</mrow>
          <mrow> = \amp \left\lbrace \left(\frac{x}{B},y\right):x\in D\right\rbrace</mrow>
        </md>
         
      </p>
    </proof>
  </p>

</section>